// @test regression/INV071-forin-loop-var-element-type
// @description A for-in loop variable carries the collection's element type, so misuse is type-checked. `for v in array<float>` makes `v` a series float and `str.length(v)` is TV's CE10123 (probed 2026-06-19); same for the tuple `for [i, s] in` value. Previously the loop var was typed "unknown" and all such misuse slipped through. See investigations/INV071-forin-loop-var-element-type/notes.md.
// @expects parse: success
// @expects error: line=6, column=21, message="type was used but a "
// @expects error: line=8, column=21, message="type was used but a "
//@version=6
indicator("x")
floats = array.from(1.0, 2.0)
a = 0
for v in floats
    a := str.length(v)
for [i, s] in floats
    a := str.length(s)
plot(a)
